title: William Walz
text: Hi, this is for my Data Science class! I’ve made two visualizations of random TidyTuesday datasets.

title: Data Visualization 1
text:

artists <- read_csv("artists.csv")

Rows: 3532 Columns: 9
── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Delimiter: ","
chr (6): name, gender, dates, placeOfBirth, placeOfDeath, url
dbl (3): id, yearOfBirth, yearOfDeath

ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.

top_birth_years <- artists |>
  filter(!is.na(yearOfBirth)) |>
  group_by(yearOfBirth) |>
  summarize(n = n()) |>
  arrange(desc(n)) |>
  head(5)

top_birth_years

# A tibble: 5 × 2
  yearOfBirth     n
        <dbl> <int>
1        1936    49
2        1930    48
3        1928    45
4        1967    45
5        1938    41



ggplot(top_birth_years, aes(x = reorder(as.factor(yearOfBirth), n), y = n)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelBlue") +
  labs(
    title = "Top 5 Years of Artist Births",
    x = "Year of Birth",
    y = "Number of Artists"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
